1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 e5 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. Bd3
(8. a4 {is the most played, preventing Black from developing the queenside
actively} Be7 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O exf4 $1 {this gives Black easy development
and pressure against the e4-pawn} 11. Kh1 Nc5 12. Bxf4 Bg4 {[%cal Yg4h5,Yh5g6,
Gf8e8,Ga8c8]}) 8... b5 $1 {Black takes his chance.} 9. O-O Be7 10. Qe1 O-O 11.
Kh1 Bb7 12. a3 Re8 $1 {[%cal Ye5f4,Ge8e1] Black threatens to open the e-file
and build up annoying pressure on e4.} (12... exf4 13. Bxf4 Re8 {this move
order gives White more freedom to arrange his pieces} 14. Nd4 {[%cal Yd4f5]} g6
15. Qf2 {[%cal Ga1e1] with nice development}) 13. fxe5 {Other moves would
leave the e4 pawn weak.} (13. Bd2 {for example} exf4 14. Bxf4 Bf8 15. Nd4 {
Black is one tempo ahead now and can play} d5 $1 {with advantage} 16. e5 Bd6 $1
{[%csl Ge5]} 17. Nf3 Bxe5 18. Bxe5 Ng4 $17) (13. f5 $2 {is also bad, due to} d5
$1 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 $17) 13... dxe5 14. Qg3 (14. Bg5 {is also
played. White aims to provoke} h6 15. Be3 {[%csl Yh6][%cal Ge1g3,Yf3h4,Yh4f5]
as the pawn become a target in some positions after Nh4-f5 or Qg3, for example.
But a good solution for Black is} (15. Bd2 Nc5 $132 {[%csl Yd3,Ye4]}) 15... Bc5
$1 $146 {exchanging the dark-squared bishops improves Black's position and
reduces White's potential of an initiative, as this bishop is an important
attacking piece} 16. Nh4 (16. Bd2 Bd4 {[%cal Yd7c5]} 17. Nh4 Nc5 18. Rd1 Nxd3
19. cxd3 Bc8 $1 {[%csl Gf5] and Black is fine}) 16... g6 $1 {Black is able to
prevent Nf5} 17. Bxc5 (17. Bxh6 Ng4 18. Bd2 Bf2 $1 19. Rxf2 Qxh4 $19 {is the
tactical reason}) 17... Nxc5 18. Qf2 Nxd3 19. cxd3 Re6 20. Rad1 Qe7 {[%csl Gd3]
[%cal Ye6d6,Ya8d8] Black is fine}) 14... Rc8 (14... Nc5 {was also very strong,
attacking d3 and e4 immediatelly} 15. Bh6 Bf8 16. Bg5 h6 $1 17. Bxf6 (17. Bxh6
Nxd3 18. Rad1 Qb6 $1 $19 {[%cal Gf6h5,Yb6h6]}) 17... Qxf6 18. Nh4 Qg5 19. Qf2
Kh7 $1 {[%cal Ya8d8] with advantage for Black}) 15. Bh6 $2 (15. Nxe5 {is bad
in view of} Nxe5 16. Qxe5 Bb4 $1 {and Black regains the material with a much
better position} 17. Qf5 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Bxe4 19. Bxe4 Rxe4 20. Bg5 Re6 $17 {
[%csl Rc2,Rc3]}) (15. Nh4 $6 Nxe4 $1 {wins a pawn for Black} 16. Nxe4 Bxh4 17.
Qh3 Nf8 $15) (15. Be3 Nc5 {also seems better for Black} 16. Bh6 Bf8 17. Rad1
Qc7 {[%cal Gf6h5]} 18. Nd2 Nh5 19. Qf3 Nf4 $1 {a nice and instructive sacrifice
} 20. Bxf4 exf4 21. Qxf4 Qxf4 22. Rxf4 Bd6 $17 {[%cal Gd6e5]}) 15... Nh5 $1 {
Black is able to improve his pieces now.} 16. Qh3 Ndf6 17. Bg5 Qd7 $1 {Another
precise move.} 18. Qh4 ({the simplifications} 18. Qxd7 Nxd7 19. Bxe7 Rxe7 {
[%cal Yd7c5,Gh5f6,Gh5f4] would result in a very nice position for Black, as
the knights now have many squares, which shows how important the dark-squared
bishop was in White's position} 20. Rad1 Nc5 21. Rfe1 g6 22. Kg1 Nf6 $15 {
only Black's position can be improved here, which is a great practical
advantage in the endgame}) 18... Qe6 19. Nd5 $6 {White should look for
something active, or his position will become very unpleasant.} ({for example} 
19. Rad1 h6 20. Bd2 Rcd8 21. Qe1 Nf4 $17) (19. a4 $1 {was a better version
compared to the game} b4 20. Nd5 h6 (20... Bxd5 21. exd5 Qxd5 22. Bxa6 Rxc2 23.
Rad1 $132 {and White is active}) 21. Nxf6+ Nxf6 22. Bxf6 Bxf6 23. Qf2 $15 {
Black is still better in view of the weaknened dark squares, but White is also
solid}) 19... Bxd5 20. exd5 Qxd5 21. Rae1 e4 $5 (21... Bd8 $142 $17 {just
protecting the pawn was very good}) 22. Bxe4 Nxe4 23. Bxe7 $2 {The decisive
mistake.} (23. Qxe4 {was the best chance for White} Qxe4 24. Rxe4 Bxg5 25.
Rxe8+ Rxe8 26. Nxg5 Re2 $1 27. Nxf7 Nf6 28. Ng5 Rxc2 $15 {Black is still
better, but White has some chances to hold the endgame}) (23. Rxe4 Bxg5 24.
Rxe8+ Rxe8 25. Qxg5 Qc4 $1 {[%csl Yc2,Yf1][%cal Gh5f4] and Black coordinates
the pieces with some threats}) 23... Rc4 $1 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge4g3,Gc4h4]
Probably the move missed by White. Black is winning.} 24. g4 (24. Bg5 Neg3+ $1
25. hxg3 Rxh4+ $19 {the detail is that Black wins the queen with check}) (24.
Kg1 $1 {was the only try, but Black is still winning after} Neg3 25. Qg5 Qxg5
26. Bxg5 Ne2+ $1 27. Kh1 h6 28. Bh4 g5 29. Bf2 Rxc2 $17) 24... Nf4 {[%cal
Gc4c2,Yf4g6]} 25. Bg5 Ng6 26. Qh5 Ng3+ $1 27. hxg3 Rxe1 0-1

