1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 b5 8. O-O
(8. f4 $6 {immediately is risky for White, as an old game by Fischer
illustrates very well} Bb7 9. f5 e5 10. Nde2 Nbd7 $1 (10... Nxe4 11. Bd5 $1 {
offers good compensation for White}) 11. Bg5 Be7 {[%csl Ye4] and White has
problems with e4 already} 12. Ng3 (12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Qd3 Rc8 14. O-O O-O 15.
Ng3 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 a5 $1 $36 {[%cal Ya5a4,Yb5b4] ;Malik,J (2352)-Cernousek,L 
(2438)/CZE-chT 1112 2011 (3.7)/0-1}) 12... Rc8 13. O-O h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4] an
unexpected move that creates very unpleasant problems for White} 14. h4 (14.
Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Qd3 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 Rxc3 $1 17. bxc3 h4 18. Ne2 Bxe4 {[%cal Yh4h3]}
19. Qh3 Rh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5g5] with a winning attack for Black}) 14... b4 $1 15.
Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nd5 Bxh4 17. Nxh5 Qg5 $19 {Byrne,R-Fischer,R/Interzonal-07+ 1967
(12)/0-1 Black was totally winning}) 8... Be7 9. f4 (9. Qf3 {is the main line})
9... O-O 10. f5 $2 {Normally, rushing with f4-f5 isn't a good idea for White,
but Black should know how to answer it.} b4 $1 11. Na4 e5 $1 {This is the best
reaction to White's idea. White's knights will have a hard time reaching d5.}
12. Ne2 Bb7 13. Ng3 Nbd7 $1 {Black continues his development in a simple way.
Besides the pressure on e4, White has another annoying problem: The Na4 is out
of play.} (13... Nxe4 $2 {is bad because after} 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Qg4 $1 {
Black has unnecessarily lost his positional advantage and White obtains nice
counterplay for the pawn} d5 16. Bh6 Bf6 17. Bxg7 $1 Bxg7 18. f6 Bg6 19. fxg7
Kxg7 20. Rad1 $44) 14. Qf3 ({an encounter of two legends went} 14. Qe1 a5 15.
c4 Qc7 16. Qe2 Rfc8 17. Bg5 Nc5 18. Rac1 (18. Nxc5 Qxc5+ 19. Kh1 a4 {[%csl Rc4]
}) 18... h6 19. Be3 Ncd7 $1 {Black takes away the exchange offer and the Na4
problem persists} 20. Bf2 Ra6 21. Rc2 Qb8 $1 {nice regroupment of pieces by
Ivanchuk, to increase the pressure over e4} 22. Re1 Qa8 23. Qd3 $2 (23. h3 $142
$15) 23... Ng4 $1 {[%csl Gf2]} 24. Nf1 Ndf6 25. Nd2 Nxf2 26. Kxf2 Bc6 27. Rcc1
Qa7+ 28. Ke2 Rd8 {[%cal Gd6d5] ;Anand,V (2635)-Ivanchuk,V (2695)/Linares 09th
1991 (8)/0-1 and soon Black had a direct attack against the king}) 14... Bc6
15. Be3 Qc7 ({Black is not able to win the knight with} 15... Qa5 {in view of
the resource} 16. a3 $1 {[%cal Ya1a8]}) 16. c3 a5 $1 {[%csl Ya4] It is
important to keep the knight on a4out of play. Black doesn't need to rush here,
just keep improving his position. White is practically playing a piece down.}
17. c4 Qb7 18. Bc2 {White has the dream to someday play b3 and rescue the
knight via b2, but this task is anything but easy.} Rac8 19. Rac1 (19. b3 $2
Bxa4 20. bxa4 Rxc4 $19) 19... h6 {Preventing the pin, although it wouldn't
help White.} (19... Rc7 20. Bg5 h6 21. Bh4 Rfc8 22. Qe2 Qa6 $17) 20. Qe2 {
White is at least able to play b3 now.} Rc7 (20... Nxe4 21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. Bxh6
$1) 21. b3 $2 {This is a mistake, but try to play a whole game with a useless
trapped knight on the edge of the board... It is not an easy task, and players
tend to become annoyed enough to make big mistakes in such cases.} (21. Bf2 {
keeps everything defended for White, although in practice his positions seems
always unpleasant to play. The position is also very similar to the game
Anand-Ivanchuk mentioned in the notes to 14.Qf3. A possible follow-up could be}
Qa6 22. Rfe1 Rfc8 {[%cal Yc6a4,Gc7c4] somehow White still holds, but it is
evident that he is on the edge of the precipice, for example} 23. Bb3 Qb7 24.
Bc2 Ne8 $5 {[%cal Ye7g5]} 25. Be3 Bh4 $1 26. Bf2 Nef6 27. Kh1 Bxg3 28. Bxg3
Bxa4 29. Bxa4 Qxe4 $1 30. Qxe4 Nxe4 31. Rxe4 Nc5 32. Bc2 Nxe4 33. Bxe4 Rxc4 34.
Re1 Rc1 $19) 21... Bxa4 $1 22. bxa4 {In this case, the medicine was even worse
than the disease: White has multiple weaknesses in his camp, but his position
is not as solid as in the previous note. Polugaevsky knows how to increase his
advantage, and shows it in an instructive way.} Qc6 23. Qd1 Rd8 24. Re1 Nc5 25.
Bf2 Rdd7 26. h3 Rc8 $1 27. Kh2 Bd8 $1 {[%cal Gd8b6] Black's next step is to
exchange the dark-squared bishops, a typical idea in such structures, that
leaves White's position even more exposed.} 28. Bxc5 $2 {Again making things
easier for Black, as the weaknesses on the dark-squares will not disappear
after this move. It seems that White was so scared about the opponent's
threats in this game, that this made him take desperate decisions, offering
very weak resistance.} (28. Ra1 Bb6 29. Nh5 $5 {was still a better chance} Bd8
(29... Nxh5 30. Qxh5 Nd3 $1 31. Bxd3 Bxf2 32. Re2 Bd4 33. Rf1 {[%cal Yf5f6]})
30. Nxf6+ Bxf6 31. Rb1 $15) 28... dxc5 29. Qe2 Rd4 $19 {White is just
defenceless against the invasion on the dark-squares now.} 30. Rcd1 Qa6 31.
Rxd4 $2 (31. Bb3 {would force Black to find the path to victory, although it
is not so difficult} Qc6 32. Qf3 Be7 33. Kh1 Rcd8 34. Kg1 Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ye7g5,
Ye7h4] and Black finds the decisive regroupment of pieces} 35. Nf1 Bg5 {
[%cal Ge8f6]} 36. Rxd4 Rxd4 37. Qe2 Nf6 38. Ng3 Bf4 $19) 31... cxd4 {[%csl Gc5,
Yd4][%cal Yf6d7,Yd7c5] Black now has the excellent c5-square and a strong
passed pawn on d4.} 32. Bb3 Qb6 33. Rd1 Nd7 34. Nh1 Nc5 35. Nf2 Qc6 36. Qc2 Bg5
$1 {Soon everything falls.} 37. g3 Be3 38. Nd3 Nxb3 39. axb3 Qxe4 40. Nxb4 Qf3
41. Nd3 e4 42. Ne5 Qxf5 43. Ng4 d3 44. Qg2 Bc5 {Although White has offered
weak resistance in this game, I think it is a very instructive example of how
to face this early f4-f5 as Black.} 0-1

