1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. O-O Be7 8. Bb3
O-O 9. f4 b5 10. e5 dxe5 11. fxe5 Nfd7 12. Bf4 ({I consider} 12. Be3 $5 {
to be the best option for White, sacrificing the pawn for active development.
Even then, Black has a good game} Nxe5 13. Qh5 Nbc6 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Rf3 {
[%cal Yf3h3]} Qd6 $1 {an important idea} (15... g6 $5 {seems a bit risky to me}
) 16. Rh3 h6 17. Bxh6 Qc5+ $1 18. Qxc5 Bxc5+ 19. Be3 Bxe3+ 20. Rxe3 Rd8 $15 {
[%csl Yb3][%cal Gc8b7,Gc6e7] ;Ashton,A (2294)-Gallagher,J (2565)/SUI-ch int
Saas Almagell 2005 (6)/0-1 White managed to get rid of his weak e5-pawn
keeping the material balance, but the endgame still seems a bit unpleasant
from a practical point of view, as the Bb3 remained a bit clumsy and Black's
pieces have more freedom -}) 12... Nc5 {[%csl Yb3] The light-squared bishop
doesn't seem particularly scary, but this a good way to prevent sacrifices on
e6 and continue development. Black always has the opportunity to grab the
bishop pair, too.} 13. Rf3 {White needs to try something on the kingside, or
his position will simply be bad.} (13. Nce2 {[%cal Yc2c3,Yb3c2] is an idea to
rescue the bishop via c2 and transfer the pieces to the kingside, but Black
can always take on b3 before White realizes his dreams} Bb7 14. Qe1 (14. c3
Nxb3 $15) 14... Nc6 15. Nxc6 (15. Rd1 Qc7 $146 16. Qg3 Nxb3 17. axb3 Nxd4 18.
Nxd4 Be4 $1 $15) 15... Bxc6 16. Rd1 Qc7 17. c3 Nxb3 18. axb3 Be4 $1 $17 {
this bishop is useful for attack and defence. Black is better}) 13... b4 14.
Nce2 Bb7 15. Rh3 Be4 $1 {[%cal Ge4g6,Gb7e4] A nice idea to remember, this is
enough to prevent any active idea by White on the kingside.} 16. c3 Nxb3 17.
axb3 bxc3 18. bxc3 Qd5 $15 {[%csl Yg2] Black already has a pleasant advantage.}
19. Ng3 $2 {This is strange and bad.} (19. Re3 $1 {was the best chance,
although it is a difficult move to find over the board} Qb7 $1 (19... Bxg2 $2 {
reveals a nice resource for White} 20. Rg3 $1 Be4 21. Bh6 Bg6 22. Bxg7 $1 Kxg7
23. Nf5+ $1 {[%cal Gf5e7]}) 20. Ng3 Bg6 (20... Bxg2 21. Qg4 $44 {[%cal Yg3h5,
Yf4h6] seems dangerous for Black}) 21. Qg4 Nc6 {Black is still better, for
example} 22. h4 Bc5 $1 {[%csl Yd4]} 23. Ra4 Ne7 24. h5 Bf5 $15) 19... Bxg2 {
White for sure missed something, as he is just lost.} 20. Rh5 (20. c4 Qb7 $19)
20... Be4 21. Nxe4 Qxe4 $19 22. Qb1 Qxb1+ 23. Rxb1 Bc5 24. Be3 Nd7 25. b4 Ba7
26. c4 a5 27. b5 Rfc8 28. Nc2 Rxc4 29. Bxa7 Rxa7 30. Ne3 Rc5 31. Rh4 Nxe5 32.
Kf1 Rb7 33. Rd4 f6 0-1

