{[%csl Ge5,Ge6] The following structure is a nice example of how doubled pawns
can be beneficial in some cases. This usually arises after an exchange of the
knights on the e5-square. Black's doubled pawns not only control important
central squares but also make the idea of f2-f4-f5 impossible. Since White
usually has a knight on c3, Black can make use of the d4-square which can be
occupied by a knight. White usually tries to attack with his pieces. Such an
attack, however, is not very efficient since Black has no weaknesses.}  *

