1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 b5 8. O-O
Be7 9. Qf3 Qc7 10. Qg3 O-O 11. Bh6 Ne8 12. Rfe1 (12. Rad1 {is the main move})
12... Bf6 $1 {Giri is a very good reference to follow in the Najdorf, he
always shows a good understanding of the positions and move orders, and this is
no exception: Black defends g7 winning a tempo.} 13. Nf3 ({the natural} 13.
Rad1 $2 {is bad} Be5 $1 14. Qg4 (14. f4 Bxd4+ 15. Rxd4 Qa7 $19 {[%cal Ge6e5]})
(14. Bf4 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 b4 $1 16. Nce2 e5 $19) 14... Bxd4 $1 15. Rxd4 e5 $19 {
[%csl Rd4,Gg4]}) (13. Be3 {can be played, but relieves the pressure on g7 and
allows Black to continue his development without problems} Bd7 14. a3 Nc6 15.
Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Bf4 a5 17. Qd3 Qb7 $15 {[%cal Gb5b4,Ga5a4,Ya8d8,Ye8c7] ;Sevian,S
(2371)-Troff,K (2421)/USA-ch Saint Louis 2013 (5)/0-1}) 13... Nc6 14. Rad1 Bb7
{As White has no threats to sacrifice on e6 anymore, this bishop can be
developed in a more active way.} 15. Bf4 Rd8 16. h4 {White still looks to the
kingside, although he is lacking useful ideas.} Kh8 $1 17. Rd3 (17. Bg5 {
was White's idea, but Black can just play} h6 $1 {now} 18. Bxf6 Nxf6 {and his
position should be easier, for example} 19. a3 (19. e5 $2 dxe5 20. Rxd8 Rxd8
21. Nxe5 Nxe5 22. Qxe5 Qxe5 23. Rxe5 b4 $1 24. Ne2 Rd1+ 25. Kh2 Ng4+ $19) 19...
Ne7 20. Nd2 (20. e5 $2 Nf5 21. exd6 Rxd6 22. Qf4 Bxf3 23. Qxf3 Rfd8 $17) 20...
Qc5 (20... Ng6 $2 21. Bxe6 $1) 21. Qe3 Ng6 22. g3 Ne5 $17) 17... Ne5 $1 {
An instructive idea, as the transformation of the pawn structure leaves
White's pieces without prospects of improving.} 18. Bxe5 (18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. Bg5
{seems equal, and was maybe a safer option}) 18... dxe5 19. Rxd8 {White
probably has thought this was good, as he can occupy the d-file, but actually, it gives Black more freedom to develop his pieces.} ({so,} 19. a3 {should be
better, for example} g6 (19... Nd6 20. Nxe5) 20. Red1 Rxd3 21. cxd3 {and the
position seems equal}) 19... Qxd8 20. Rd1 (20. Nxe5 Bxh4 21. Qe3 Bg5 22. Qd3 (
22. f4 Be7 $17 {[%cal Gd8c7,Ge7c5]}) 22... Nd6 23. Rd1 Be7 $15 {[%cal Yd8c7]})
20... Qc7 21. a3 g6 $1 {[%cal Ye8g7,Yg7h5] Giri finds a way to improve the
knight.} 22. Ng5 (22. Qh2 {[%cal Gh4h5] was the better try, but a difficult
move to find} h5 (22... Ng7 23. g4 $1 {is the idea}) 23. Qg3 {and the Ne8 is
deprived of h5}) 22... Bc8 $1 {[%csl Ye6] Giri again finds a nice preventive
move, this time overprotecting e6 against possible resources.} (22... h6 23.
Bxe6 $5 {could be White's idea} hxg5 24. Rd7 Qc6 25. Rxf7 Qxe6 26. Rxb7 {
although Black should be technically winning}) 23. Qd3 {White managed to
regroup the pieces, but due to Black's solid structure, it is very difficult to imagine a way of making further progress for him.} (23. a4 $5 {was more active,
but after} h6 24. Nf3 b4 25. Nb1 a5 26. Nbd2 Ba6 $17 {Black keeps a big
advantage}) 23... Be7 {[%cal Ge8f6] Finally the knight is back in the game.}
24. Qe2 Nf6 25. Rd3 h6 26. Nf3 Kg7 $17 {Black has more than one plan available:
he can try Nd7-c5, or Bc5 and Ng4, or even prepare the advance of pawns on the
queenside, all of these ideas seem very promising. Nothing similar is
available for White, so it is fair to say that Black has a clear advantage.} 27.
Nb1 {White looks for a regroupment of pieces, but he is just unable to
accomplish it.} Bc5 $1 28. Nh2 (28. Nbd2 $2 Ng4 $19 {[%csl Rf2] simply wins})
28... a5 (28... Nh5 {[%cal Gh5f4] was also very strong}) 29. c3 Ba6 {[%cal
Ga6f1] Black's moves are all natural and strong.} 30. Rf3 Qc6 31. Nd2 $2 (31.
Bc2 $142 b4 32. Qe1 bxa3 33. Nxa3 Rb8 $19) 31... a4 $1 ({White was probably
counting only on} 31... b4 32. Bc4 Bxc4 33. Qxc4) 32. Bc2 b4 $1 {White is
unable to avoid material losses.} 33. Qe1 (33. Bd3 Bxd3 34. Qxd3 bxa3 35. bxa3
Bxa3 $19) 33... bxa3 34. bxa3 Rd8 35. Ndf1 (35. Nb1 h5 $19 {White is almost in
zugzwang}) 35... Bxa3 $19 36. Qa1 Bc5 37. Bxa4 Qxe4 38. Ng3 Qxh4 39. Bc6 {
A highly instructive example of how to handle such positions by Giri.} 0-1

