1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Qb6 ({
another popular variation that reaches this structure is} 7... Qc7 8. Bxf6 gxf6
{although White has not sacrificed b2 in this case}) 8. Qd2 Qxb2 9. Nb3 $6 {
I think this is a bit inferior to developing the rook.} (9. Rb1 Qa3 10. Bxf6
gxf6 {seems to be a better version for White: He has kept the centralized
knight on d4 and developed one more piece. A recent game went} 11. Be2 h5 $1
12. O-O Qa5 13. Kh1 Nc6 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Qd4 Be7 16. Na4 $44 {[%csl Yb6] ;
Kokarev,D (2608) -Leko,P (2691)/TCh-ESP Div Honor 2018 2018 (3.3)/1/2-1/2})
9... Qa3 (9... Be7 $4 {would fall in the only trap} 10. a3 $18 {[%csl Gb2]
[%cal Ya1a2]}) 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Be2 h5 $1 {We already know how important it
is to prevent the light-squared bishop from coming to h5.} 12. O-O {White has
some compensation for the pawn, of course, as he has developed all his pieces
while Black kept making moves with the queen and pawns. But the typical way of
exploiting a lead in development is by opening lines in the opponent's camp,
and Black is safe against this in view of his solid central pawns.} Nd7 13. f5
(13. Kh1 h4 $1 {an interesting way of looking for counterplay on the kingside}
14. h3 (14. Rad1 h3 $1 15. g3 b5 {[%cal Gc8b7] ;Gashimov,V (2625)-Palac,M 
(2561)/EU-ch 7th Kusadasi 2006 (7)/0-1 the bishop is more active on b7 now due
to the weakened diagonal -}) 14... Be7 15. Rad1 b5 $1 16. Qe3 Bb7 17. f5 Ne5 {
[%csl Ge5] ; Pruijssers, R (2261) -Senff, M (2467)/Dieren op 2005 (2)/0-1 Black
is solid enough, White soon ran out of active ideas and began to make mistakes}
) 13... Be7 {Black should forget the idea of developing the bishop to h6 with
queens on the board: It is more important to keep the center and the king safe.
} 14. Qd4 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Yc3b1] Threatening to win the queen.} (14. Kh1 {
is most played}) (14. Nb1 Qa4 $5 (14... Qb2 15. Nc3 {[%cal Ya2a3]} Qa3 16. Nb1
$11) 15. c4 Ne5 16. Nc3 Qc6 17. Kh1 $5 {is still complex}) 14... b5 $1 15. Kh1
(15. Nb1 {is harmless now due to} Qa4) (15. Rf3 {[%cal Yf3h3] ;Guseinov,G 
(2489) -Villavicencio Martinez, A (2308)/ Rilton Cup 31st 2001 (5)/1/2-1/2 had
an idea similar to the game - Black could obtain a great advantage now with}
Ne5 16. Rh3 h4 17. Rf1 Bd8 $1 18. Rf4 Rb8 $1 19. Kh1 Bb6 20. Qd1 Ke7 21. Rfxh4
Rxh4 22. Rxh4 b4 23. Nb1 Qxa2 $19) 15... Ne5 $1 {Black is very solid now, and
if the material was even we could say that he was in a good position, but he
is even a pawn up.} 16. Rf4 {[%cal Yf4h4]} h4 $1 17. Raf1 Bd7 $17 18. Nd1 {
Aiming to concentrate his forces on the kingside.} (18. h3 Rc8 {seems almost
winning for Black, for example} 19. fxe6 fxe6 20. Qe3 Qb4 21. Nd1 Rxc2 $19)
18... Rc8 19. Ne3 Qa4 $1 {Disturbing White's forces.} 20. fxe6 fxe6 21. Qd1 (
21. Qxa4 bxa4 22. Nd4 Rc3 23. Ng4 Nxg4 24. Rxg4 e5 25. Nf5 Rxc2 26. Bxa6 Rxa2
$19 {[%csl Ga4]}) 21... h3 $1 22. g3 Qxa2 $19 {Black has played solidly enough
to prevent any active ideas by White, and it is time to realize the material
advantage.} 23. Nd4 Rc5 24. R4f2 Qa3 25. Nb3 Rc7 26. Ng4 Nxg4 27. Bxg4 Rc4 28.
Rf4 Qb4 29. Nd2 Rd4 30. R1f2 Qb2 31. Qf3 Ra4 32. c3 Qc1+ 33. Nf1 Rc4 34. Rxf6
Rxc3 0-1

