1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 8. Bh4
Qb6 {Maxime really trusts in this Delayed Poisoned Pawn variation. He has
played it very often and against some well-prepared guys like Giri, Nakamura, and Caruana, with a very good score.} 9. a3 Be7 10. Bf2 ({a a few months ago,
Caruana surprised him with} 10. Qd3 $5 {Caruana,F (2807)-Vachier Lagrave,M 
(2791)/Sinquefield Cup 5th 2017 (6)/1/2-1/2 but his idea didn't find followers
since then.}) 10... Qc7 11. Qf3 Nbd7 12. O-O-O b5 13. g4 Bb7 {in the later
games Vachier Lagrave has opted to develop the bishop.} 14. Bg2 {White
develops his bishop in order to make the thematic break d5 harder for Black.}
g5 {Vachier Lagrave improves his own play from his only defeat in this
variation in recent games.} ({that game went} 14... Rc8 15. Kb1 g5 16. Qh3 $1
Nc5 $2 ({in the notes of the game, GM Meier analyzes the strange move} 16...
Nh7 $5 {that was played in correspondence games and looks like the best option}
) 17. Rhe1 {White has developed all his pieces and is ready to take active
measures in the center} h5 (17... gxf4 18. g5 Nfd7 19. g6 $1 $40) 18. Nf5 $1 {
[%csl Gf5][%cal Ye1e8,Yd1d8] ; Nakamura,H (2779)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2804)/
London Classic 8th 2016 (7)/1-0 White's attack was strong and precise -}) (
14... d5 $2 {is not good anymore. After} 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Nf5 $1 {the point
behind 14.Bg2 becomes clear}) 15. h4 {Karjakin also shows excellent
preparation, as this principled move was also played by Yu Yangyi and
Naiditsch.} (15. f5 {, closing the kingside, didn't give White an advantage.}
e5 16. Nb3 h5 $5 17. h3 Rc8 18. Rhe1 {Henriquez Villagra,C (2517)-Salem,A 
(2656)/Wch Rapid Doha rapid 2016 (6)/1/2-1/2 Black could have reached a better
position with} hxg4 19. hxg4 a5 $1 $17 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gb5b4]}) (15. Qh3 {
Compared to Nakamura-Vachier Lagrave, Black has a totally adequate response now
} O-O-O $1 {Kulaots,K (2597)-Santos Ruiz,M (2473)/EU-ch 18th Minsk 2017 (3)/
0-1 suddenly, the Black king is safe and White's play on the kingside looks
unjustified}) 15... gxf4 16. g5 {White rushes to open the kingside, the only
way to take advantage of his better development.} Ne5 $1 {[%cal Yf6d7] Black
should vacate the d7 square for the other knight.} 17. Qxf4 hxg5 $146 18. hxg5
Rxh1 19. Rxh1 Nfd7 20. Kb1 O-O-O $11 {When watching the game, I was impressed
by how Vachier Lagrave made Black's challenges in this variation look easy to
solve. Black has finished his development, his king is safe and the knight is
solidly placed on e5, securing him a nice position. Besides, the e4 and g5
pawns offer some good chances in the ensuing endgame.} 21. Rh3 {Karjakin had
at least two interesting plans in this position.} (21. Nf3 $1 {would be good
to play against the blockader on e5, and Black's life is not that easy, at
least if he is hoping to play for a win} Rf8 {good prophylaxis} (21... Nxf3 22.
Bxf3 Ne5 23. Bh5 $1 {[%csl Yf7]} Rf8 24. Bd4 $1 {again aiming to eliminate the
annoying knight} Kb8 25. Be2 {[%cal Yh1h7] and it is White who is fighting for
the advantage}) (21... Kb8 22. Rh7 {[%cal Yg5g6] g5-g6 is a very unpleasant
threat, even after} Nf8 23. Rg7 Nfg6 24. Qg3 Rf8 25. Nxe5 Nxe5 26. Bd4 $36 {
White keeps some pressure}) (21... Rg8 {[%csl Yg5] counter attacking g5 seems
natural} 22. Bd4 $1 Kb8 (22... Nxf3 $2 23. Qxf3 {[%csl Rf7]}) 23. Bxe5 Nxe5 24.
Nxe5 $1 dxe5 25. Qxf7 Rxg5 26. Bf1 Bc8 27. Rh7 Bd8 $14 {forcing the trade of
the queens, and despite White keeping some advantage, Black should be able to
hold}) 22. Rh7 Qd8 $1 {[%csl Yg5] Now Black looks better organized to protect
his position and to attack the opponent's weaknesses} 23. Bh3 (23. Nxe5 Nxe5
24. Be3 Rg8 25. Rh5 {is harmless for Black}) 23... Nxf3 (23... Kb8 24. Nxe5
Nxe5) 24. Qxf3 Ne5 25. Qh5 Kb8 $1 (25... Bxg5 $2 {contains a very dangerous
and unexpected trap} 26. Nd5 $1 {[%cal Rf2b6]} Nd7 27. Bg3 $1 exd5 28. Bxd6 $40
) 26. Bg3 {The following sequence is almost forced:} Bxg5 27. Bxe5 dxe5 28.
Rxf7 Rh8 (28... Rxf7 $5 {could be a good practical solution} 29. Qxf7 Bxe4 $1
30. Qxe6 $1 Bb7 31. Qxe5+ Ka8 $14 {White is a pawn up, but I believe that
Black has good chances in this endgame, especially because of the reduced
number of pawns}) 29. Qg4 Bc8 30. Qg1 $1 {[%csl Ra7]} Be7 31. Qg3 Bd6 $14 {
White still can have some hopes due to Black's exposed king and the weak pawns,
but Black should be fine with correct defense. The bishop pair covers many
important squares.}) (21. g6 $5 Rg8 $1 {keeps everything under control for
Black, although the main line is very complicated} 22. gxf7 Rxg2 23. Nxe6 Qc4
$1 24. Rh8+ $1 (24. f8=Q+ $2 Nxf8 25. Nxf8 Qf7 $3 26. Qxf7 Nxf7 $19 {[%csl Rf2,
Rf8]}) 24... Nf8 25. Nxf8 Qf1+ 26. Be1 $1 (26. Ka2 Rxf2 $19) 26... Qxf4 (26...
Qxe1+ 27. Ka2 Rf2 28. Qh6 $1 Rxf7 29. Qe6+ Kc7 30. Ng6 $1) 27. Ng6+ Kd7 28.
Nxf4 Rg1 29. f8=Q Rxe1+ 30. Ka2 Bxf8 31. Rxf8 Bxe4 32. Nxe4 Rxe4 $11) 21... Kb8
22. Be3 Rg8 23. Rg3 Rg7 {Of course, White's position should be still fine, but
with the last moves Vachier Lagrave protected f7 and started to press g5, even
with the position remaining objectively equal, in a practical game it seems
that White is about to feel uncomfortable.} 24. Bh3 {[%cal Gh3e6]} Rh7 (24...
Nf8 $5 {[%cal Yf8h7]}) 25. Qf2 Nc5 {[%csl Ye4] And so there's also e4 to take
care about.} 26. Bg2 Qc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8g8,Gc8h8,Ye7d8,Yd8c7,Yd8b6] A nice move,
now the queen can be directed towards the kingside, and the bishop has the
excellent route d8-b6 or d8-c7 to be improved.} 27. Bc1 (27. Nb3 $5 {would
stop both plans, but at the price of damaging the queenside structure, which
is not an easy decision}) 27... Bd8 28. Nf3 Ng6 $1 {Karjakin went for Nf3 too
late, as in this position the black knight is not forced to stand on e5.} 29.
Nd4 Ne5 30. Nf3 Ng6 31. Nd4 {One more draw in London?} Bb6 {....no!} 32. Be3
Ne5 33. b3 {A clear signal that White's position is already slightly
unpleasant. I'm pretty sure that Karjakin would have preferred not to play
this move.} (33. Nf3 $2 {is bad due to} Nc4 $17 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gb6g1] and
the dangerous Bb6 prevents that White retreats his bishop to c1}) (33. Nb3 {
was the better option} Nc4 34. Bd4 Qc7 35. Nd2 $1 {and White keeps everything
under control} Ne5 36. Rh3 $11) 33... Rh4 {Vachier Lagrave steadily increases
the pressure.} 34. Nde2 $1 {Karjakin is also showing his defensive skills.} Qc7
35. Bd4 Ncd7 $1 {Forcing advantageous exchanges for Black.} (35... Nxe4 $2 {
would be a terrible mistake} 36. Nxe4 Bxe4 37. Bxe4 Bxd4 38. Qxd4 d5 39. Nc3 $1
dxe4 40. Nxe4 $14) 36. Bxb6 $6 {We know from his match against Carlsen that
Karjakin has really impressive skills to resist in passive defensive positions,
and here he goes for it. However, this endgame will be too much, even for him.}
(36. g6 $5 {looks interesting} fxg6 37. Bh3 Nc5 {Black is keeping an extra
pawn, although after} 38. Bxe6 $5 Nxe4 $1 39. Nxe4 (39. Bxb6 Nxf2 40. Bxc7+
Kxc7 $17) 39... Bxd4 40. Nxd4 Bxe4 $13 {the nature of the endgame has changed,
it looks sharper and can offer practical chances for White}) 36... Qxb6 37.
Qxb6 Nxb6 38. Nd4 Ng6 $1 {[%cal Yb6d7,Yd7e5,Gg6f4] The knight is alternating
between e5 and g6 many times in this game, always posing problems for Black.
Now it heads for f4, and the other knight will replace it on e5, with great
pressure in White's camp.} 39. Kc1 {The monarch runs to help his forces in the
center.} Nd7 40. Kd2 Nf4 41. Ke3 (41. Bf3 {is not keeping the bishop alive at
all} Ne5 $17) 41... Nxg2+ $1 {Sometimes we become a bit hypnotized by such
beautiful knights on good squares, but not strong players like Vachier Lagrave:
He understands that without this bishop, White's defense is harder, and the
e4-pawn is weaker.} 42. Rxg2 Rh3+ 43. Kd2 {And White is even more passive
than before.} (43. Nf3 $4 Ne5 44. Rf2 Ng4+ $19) 43... Ne5 44. Nde2 {The only
acceptable move in this difficult position.} (44. Rf2 Rg3 {[%cal Rg3g5]}) (44.
Rg1 {looks like another playable option, but Black has a way to keep improving
the position} Ka7 $1 45. Rg2 Kb6 $17 {[%cal Yb6c5]}) (44. g6 $5 {was maybe the
last practical chance} fxg6 45. Rf2 (45. Nxe6 Nf3+ 46. Ke2 Nh4 $1 $19 {[%cal
Gh4g2,Rh3c3]}) 45... Bc8 46. Rf6 $15) 44... Nf3+ 45. Kc1 Nh4 46. Rg1 Ng6 {
Black still didn't make much progress, but in such endgames, you don't really
need this: Only keep playing good moves and make sure that your opponent is in
an unpleasant position. In general, nerves, time and the difficulty of the
position decide the issue.} 47. Kd2 Kc7 {Finally, the king finds a useful
function: To protect the f7-pawn.} 48. Nd4 Kd7 49. Rf1 Ke7 50. Rg1 Ne5 51. Rg2
Ba8 52. Nde2 {Now, further improvements are possible.} (52. Rg1 {would offer
more chances}) 52... Nf3+ 53. Kc1 Rh1+ $1 {After bringing his king to the
center, Vachier Lagrave expels White's king.} 54. Kb2 Nh4 55. Rg4 Ng6 56. Nf4 {
Losing a pawn, but what else? There's no good advice's for White here.} (56. Ng3
Rh3 {[%cal Yg6e5]} 57. Nge2 Ne5 58. Rg2 (58. Rg3 Rxg3 59. Nxg3 Nf3 {[%csl Rg5]}
) 58... Rh4 {[%csl Re4]}) (56. Rg3 Rh4 57. Nd4 (57. Re3 Rg4) 57... Ne5 $1 (
57... Bxe4 58. Nxe4 Rxe4 59. Nc6+ {[%cal Yc6b8] with some chances}) 58. Nf3
Nxf3 59. Rxf3 Rg4 $17) 56... Nxf4 57. Rxf4 Rg1 58. Rh4 Rxg5 59. Kc1 d5 {
Black is totally winning and with the e and f-pawns passed and connected, the
technical task is not exactly difficult, so Karjakin decided to call it a day.
A nice win by Vachier Lagrave and the game had a great theoretical value, as
even if White plays the correct plan, Black seems to be ready to keep a fine
position against this aggressive variation.} 0-1

