1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {In the first database, I
wrote a quick summary of Black's main ideas and goals in the Najdorf,
explaining the reasons why I think it is the most reliable option for Black in
the Sicilian. (However, I should mention that I missed the Sveshnikov, which
seems to be the preferred choice of Magnus Carlsen). In that database, I
analyzed the positional lines, in which White wants to keep the position under
control and prevent Black from taking the initiative, playing for a small
advantage and a strategic approach. Time has come now to deal with those
uncompromising lines, in which White seeks a direct attack against the black
king, initiating a bloody battle for the initiative. Here the game tends to
develop in a very concrete way, and both sides need to search for tactical
resources and attacking ideas, instead of strategic motifs and positional
maneuvers, as in the first database. Some move orders and subtleties gain in
importance now, and strong calculation skills are required.} 6. Bg5 {Probably
the sharpest variation against the Najdorf, that experienced a new boom of
popularity in the last years after some exciting games between top GMs like
Caruana, Nakamura, Anand, etc.} (6. f4 {is an option for players that want to
avoid the most theoretical paths}) (6. Be3 {here I analyze the classical
English Attack, that arises after} e5 7. Nb3 (7. Nf3 {is the positional option
that was covered in the first database})) ({The Sozin Attack} 6. Bc4 $5 {
, which is kind of out of fashion now, but still a dangerous variation, is
also part of this database.}) (6. h3 $5 {is no less dangerous, but will be left
for the third and final database, together with some sidelines and rather
recent new attempts by White.}) *

