1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 $5 {This move is an
option for players who look for an uncompromised and aggressive set-up against
the Najdorf, but without any long theoretical discussions. It is everything
but harmless, and some creative attacking masters like Ivanchuk and Smirin
have played it successfully as White. I don't even know if it has a name,
though an online search led me to the "Amsterdam Variation". But I think this
is just because Ivanchuk has beaten the great Kasparov once in a brilliant way
with this move in Amsterdam.} e5 {Najdorf experts have played other moves as
well, but I think this is a very solid and reliable option.} (6... e6 {is more
in Scheveningen style.}) ({, and} 6... Qc7 7. Bd3 g6 {is rather in the spirit
of the Dragon variation.}) 7. Nf3 {Since White has already played f4, the
knight can stay close of the center.} (7. Nf5 $6 {seems more active, but
actually White is not so stable in the center to play this way.} Nc6 (7... Nxe4
$5 {is the more direct approach and also promises a good position for Black.})
8. Bc4 (8. Bd3 Bxf5 $1 9. exf5 Qb6 {and Black has very quick development} 10.
Qf3 O-O-O $1 11. Qf2 {Broekmeulen,J (2429)-Zwahr,P (2360) Neckar op-A 18th
2014 (8) 1/2-1/2} Qa5 12. Bd2 d5 $36 {[%cal Yf8b4]}) (8. fxe5 Nxe4 $1 9. Nxg7+
Bxg7 10. Nxe4 {Broekmeulen,J (2346)-Giri,A (2523) NBSB-chA Roosendaal rapid
2009 (5) 0-1} Qh4+ 11. Nf2 dxe5 {Black has a nice position again, for example}
12. g3 Qe7 13. Bg2 O-O 14. O-O f5 15. Be3 Be6 $15 {[%cal Ye5e4,Gc6e5]}) 8... g6
9. fxe5 (9. Ng3 Bg4 $1 10. Be2 Bxe2 11. Ngxe2 Qb6 $1 {, and White will face
some problems in development.}) 9... Nxe5 10. Ne3 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. Bb3 {
we've already seen a similar structure to this one in the first database. I
think this is even an improved version for Black, as the bishop is better
placed on g7 compared to those positions in which it was on e7.} Be6 $1 13.
Ned5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 {Monpeurt, C (2175)-Haussernot,C (2198) ch-FRA w 2018 2018 
(4.3) 1-0. In this position,} Ng4 $1 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Gd8b6] would show quite
well the advantages of having the bishop on g7 and how Black can exploit the
open diagonals in White's camp, for example} 15. Qe2 (15. Kh1 $2 Qh4 {[%csl
Rh2][%cal Gg4f2]}) (15. h3 Bxd5 16. Qxg4 Qb6+ $1 17. Kh1 Bxb3 18. axb3 Qc6 {
[%csl Gc2,Ge4]} 19. c3 Rae8 $17) 15... Bd4+ $1 16. Kh1 Nxh2 $1 $40) 7... Nbd7
8. a4 {Usually after Nbd7 Black is ready for ...b5, so White prevents the
advance.} (8. Bd3 {allows a better version for Black:} Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Kh1
b5 $1 {Now Black manages to develop his pieces in an active way:} 11. a3 ({
White can play} 11. Qe1 {, but he can't really use the tempo of a2-a3 to get
an advantage.} Bb7 12. fxe5 dxe5 13. Bg5 Nc5 $5 {[%cal Yd8c7,Gb5b4] Cigan,S 
(2370)-Ftacnik,L (2580) AUT-chT2S 9596 1995 0-1, and Black is ok as a3 will be
more or less necessary, for example} 14. Nxe5 b4 15. Nd1 Nfxe4 16. Bxe7 Qxe7
$11) (11. a4 $5 {is a standard reaction for White after b5, but it is harmless
in this position} b4 12. Ne2 Bb7 13. Ng3 Nc5 {[%csl Ye4] Black is fine.
Ponkratov,P (2603)-Kokarev,D (2612) Voronezh op-A 14th 2010 (6) 0-1}) 11... Bb7
12. Qe1 Re8 $1 {[%cal Ye8e1] a recurring idea in this variation is to place
the rook on the e-file in order to threaten pressure against the weakened
e4-pawn, thus forcing White to relieve the tension with} 13. fxe5 (13. Bd2 exf4
14. Bxf4 Bf8 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Yd7c5,Gd6d5] looks nice for Black.}) 13... dxe5
14. Bg5 (14. Qg3 {is not really dangerous} Rc8 15. Bh6 Nh5 16. Qh3 Ndf6 17. Bg5
Qd7 $1 18. Qh4 Qe6 {White tried to force complications now with} 19. Nd5 $6
Bxd5 20. exd5 Qxd5 21. Rae1 {but after} e4 $1 22. Bxe4 Nxe4 23. Bxe7 Rc4 $1 $17
{[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge4g3] Black was much better - Maryasin,B (2340)-Szabo,K 
(2508) Gibraltar Masters 7th 2009 (7) 0-1}) 14... h6 15. Be3 {[%cal Yf3h4,
Yh4f5] White expects to play Nh4-f5 or Qg3 in the next moves, exploiting h6 as
a point of contact in Black's camp, but this problem can be solved in advance
by means of} (15. Bd2 Nc5 $132 {[%csl Yd3,Ye4]}) 15... Bc5 $1 $146 16. Nh4 (16.
