Rgd3 Rxd3 24. Rxd3 Kf8 $15) 17... Qc5+ $1 {The important detail about 15.Qd6
is that Black manages to exchange queens by force, thus forcing favorable
simplifications.} 18. Qxc5 Bxc5+ 19. Be3 Bxe3+ 20. Rxe3 Rd8 $15 {[%csl Yb3]
Black has a small advantage due to the open file and the slightly misplaced
white bishop on b3. White should be ok if he plays well, but in practice, with
one or two mistakes, his position can become very unpleasant. Black won a very
instructive endgame in Ashton, A (2294)-Gallagher, J (2565) SUI-ch int Saas
Almagell 2005 (6) 0-1.} *

