1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 {Probably the most
aggressive move against the Najdorf. The main difference from the previous
lines is that with 6.Bg5 White plays for quick development AND the initiative
from the very first moves, which leads to very open and sharp battles with a
lot of tension and tactical resources for both sides. This is the move
indicated for attacking players, as the recipe for White is very simple:
Develop quickly and in the most active way possible, advance pawns, sacrifice
pieces, attack, and mate. The positions arising are quite complex and one
mistake can ruin everything for any side, so even players that are not so well
prepared, but trust in their tactical vision and attacking skill, like this
line.} e6 (6... Nbd7 {is another interesting, more flexible way to face 6.Bg5,
in which both sides have a lot of freedom to choose how to continue their
development in the next moves.}) 7. Qf3 $5 {Let's start with sidelines for
White in the 7th move. There are some options, of which this seems to be the
most popular. White chooses to develop his pieces rapidly and before advancing
the f-pawn, although he expects to play f4 anyway after moving the queen to g3.
This is a worthy option for players that want to avoid long theoretical and
forced lines like the Poisoned Pawn Variation, for example.} (7. Qd2 {is more
common in set-ups like the English Attack. In comparison the bishop's
position on g5 can only be favorable for black.} h6 $1 {the most direct,
grabbing the bishop pair} 8. Bxf6 (8. Bh4 $2 Nxe4 $1) (8. Be3 Ng4 9. O-O-O Be7
10. f4 Nxe3 11. Qxe3 Qc7 12. Kb1 b5 $132 {Petenyi,T (2454) -Cernousek,L (2450)
TCh-CZE Extraliga 2017-18 2017 (10.3) 0-1}) 8... Qxf6 9. O-O-O {[%cal Yf2f4,
Yf1c4,Yh1e1,Ye4e5] White has given up the dark-squared bishop, but in return
obtained a visible advantage in development. Now he hopes to centralize his
forces and open the position, so Black should hurry and play} Nc6 $1 {, aiming
for exchanges.} 10. Nb3 (10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. f4 {transposes to a line analyzed
in the next chapter}) 10... Qd8 $1 {This move should be remembered. Although
Black is behind in development, he invests another tempo in a queen move. The
reasoning is that in Sicilian positions, the queen belongs to the queenside,
where it helps to generate counterplay against the opponent's king. Regarding
the development, thanks to the pair e6/d6 Black has a solid position and there
is no easy way for White to launch an attack or break into his camp.} (10...
Be7 $2 {[%csl Yf6] would just leave the queen misplaced on the kingside.}) 11.
f4 Be7 12. Kb1 b5 $1 13. g4 (13. Bd3 b4 14. Ne2 O-O 15. g4 a5 {seems faster
for Black} 16. Nbd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Qb6 18. Nf3 a4 19. g5 hxg5 20. Rhg1 {Rogic,D
(2591)-Jankovic,A (2560) CRO-chT1A 19th 2010 (6) 1-0} Bb7 21. Nxg5 a3 $1 $17 {
[%cal Gb6d4]}) 13... b4 $1 {since the Black king is safe on e8, he can come
first on the queenside.} 14. Ne2 (14. Na4 $146 {should be the best move to
block the pawns, but the knight is out of play on a4 now.} Rb8 15. h4 e5 16. f5
Bd7 $17 {[%csl Ra4]}) 14... e5 $1 $146 {[%cal Gc8g4] White has many problems}
15. fxe5 (15. f5 a5 $17 {[%cal Gd8b6,Ya5a4]}) 15... dxe5 16. Qxd8+ Nxd8 17. h3
h5 $1 $17 {It is going to be a difficult ending for White, due to the many
weaknesses in his camp and the Black bishop pair.}) (7. Qe2 {this has ideas
similar to the text. The queen is less active on e2 compared to f3 and White
loses some ideas like the typical sacrifices Bxb5. But he can advance the
f-pawn more easily and transpose to typical 6.Bg5 lines and the queen might
be able to support e4-e5 in some positions.} h6 8. Bh4 ({Trading on f6 would
