1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 {
This move, associated with the next, was largely ignored in the past, but
gained an explosion of popularity in the last years, notably by the games of
French GM Maxime Vachier-Lagrave, who plays it almost exclusively. The
insertion of h6 adds important details and resources to the old Poisoned Pawn
Variation, and I consider it a reliable choice and a good recommendation
against 6.Bg5. In this chapter, we will deal with more sidelines for White,
before plunging into the long theoretical debates of the main lines.} 8. Bh4 (
8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qd2 Nc6 $1 {Aiming for quick development. A similar position
was analyzed after 8.Bxf6 in the subline 7.Qd2 of the previous chapter, but
subtleties in move orders are very important in many Sicilian lines. Compared
to that position White has played f4 instead of 0-0-0, which allows} 10. Nf3 $1
{that is a better square than b3 for the knight. From here it supports
advances in the center and on the kingside.} (10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. O-O-O {was
once played against me. I confess that I was not aware of Black's plans at the
time but intuitively realized that} Qd8 $1 {was the right move, as the queen
is better placed close to the queenside, especially after the opening of the
b-file} 12. Bc4 {[%cal Yc4b3] this seems the most natural, the bishop will be
useful to keep the king safe and can also pressure the kingside} Be7 13. Kb1
O-O 14. g4 d5 $1 15. Bb3 a5 {Black must look for counterplay in the center and
on the queenside} 16. g5 $2 {White expected to accelerate his attack with this
idea, but it doesn't work} ({instead,} 16. h4 $1 {seemed quite dangerous for
me during the game. Of course, accepting the pawn is suicide.} Bb4 $5 {[%cal
Ga5a4]} 17. a4 Rb8 18. g5 h5 $1 {the kingside must stay as closed as possible}
19. f5 $1 Qd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6e5] the position is very tense, but Black is very
solid in the center and there is no easy way for White to break through on the
kingside, for example} 20. Rh3 {[%cal Gd2e2]} Qe5 $15) 16... hxg5 17. Rhg1 d4
$1 {a nice resource to disturb White plans} 18. Ne2 (18. Qxd4 Qxd4 19. Rxd4 Bc5
$19 {[%csl Gd4,Gg1]}) 18... c5 19. fxg5 g6 $1 {not only the king is very safe
now, Black also has chances to develop a dangerous initiative on the queenside.
} 20. Nf4 Qc7 21. Bc4 Ba6 $1 22. Bxa6 Rxa6 23. Rdf1 Rb8 $40 {[%cal Ya6b6] ;
Calcado,A (2143)-Quintiliano Pinto,R (2484) Florianopolis op 3rd 2017 (1) 0-1})
(10. Nb3 Qd8 $1 11. O-O-O {transposes to a line analyzed in the previous
chapter}) 10... Qd8 $1 (10... g5 $5 {seems to be a very practical and playable
pawn sacrifice. Black has won many games with this line.}) 11. O-O-O Bd7 {
since White has shown some intentions of advancing pawns on the kingside,
Black should look for a safe place for his king on the other side} 12. Kb1 (12.
Bd3 Qc7 13. Rhe1 O-O-O 14. Kb1 Kb8 15. Ne2 Be7 16. Ned4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Bf6 $11 {
[%csl Gd7,Gf6] ;Stavnjak,L (2246) -Kozul,Z (2614) BIH-chT 15th 2016 (2.1) 0-1})
(12. g3 Qc7 13. Bh3 O-O-O 14. f5 Kb8 15. Ne2 Be7 16. Kb1 Ne5 $1 17. Ned4 Nc4
18. Qf2 Qb6 $1 $19 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Ye6e5] ;Olafsson,H (2520)-Kasparov,G (2805)
Reykjavik TV rapid 1995 (3) 0-1}) (12. f5 Qa5 $1 {[%csl Ye5] Taking control of
the e5 square.} 13. Bc4 Be7 14. Kb1 O-O-O 15. g4 Ne5 $1 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Qe2
Kb8 18. Rhf1 Bf6 19. Rf3 Rc8 20. Bb3 Rc6 $17 {[%cal Yh8c8] ;Babaev,T (2311)
-Guseinov,G (2645) AZE-ch 71st Baku 2016 (2) 0-1}) 12... Qc7 {White has
different move orders, but his idea is to advance the pawns on the kingside}
13. Qe3 (13. h4 O-O-O 14. h5 Kb8 15. Be2 Be7 16. g4 Bc8 17. g5 Rhe8 {Black
ignores the pressure on the kingside and goes for central play} 18. Qe3 Qa5 19.
Qg1 $2 d5 $1 $132 {Black achieves nice counterplay with this move}) 13... Be7
14. g4 O-O-O 15. h4 Kb8 16. Be2 Bc8 {the moves Qd8-c7, Bd7, 0-0-0, Kb8 and Bc8
are almost automatic, as it is the most natural way to develop Black's pieces}
17. Rhf1 Qa5 18. g5 hxg5 19. hxg5 Rh3 20. Rh1 Rdh8 {Black is at least ok: His
pieces are well developed and the bishop pair is an advantage to use in the
endgames, as the pawn structure remains flexible - Verduga Zavala, D (2356)
-Bruzon Batista,L (2614) Morelia op 2nd 2007 (5) 0-1}) 8... Qb6 $1 {This is
the favorite move of Vachier-Lagrave and my recommendation. It is also
recommended by GM Milos Pavlovic in his recent book about the Najdorf. Apart
from its objective soundness it is appealing that it's less heavy on theory than
other variations.} 9. Qd3 $5 {[%csl Yd3,Gg6] This is an important line. White
aims to exploit the drawback of having the pawn on h6: The g6-square is weak
in some positions.} (9. Bxf6 gxf6 {this is not dangerous but was played by a
few grandmasters, as some players like to play this structure with queens on
the board. But b2 is still hanging...} 10. Qd2 (10. a3 {contains the same trap
as the main line with 9.a3, but Black simply plays} Nc6 $1 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {
[%csl Gb2][%cal Gb6e3] with a good position}) 10... Qxb2 11. Nb3 $5 (11. Rb1
Qa3 {transposes to a sideline analyzed in the next chapter}) 11... Qa3 12. Be2
h5 $1 {as seen in other positions, Black should prevent the bishop from coming
to h5} 13. O-O $44 {we have a typical position for this line: White has
sacrificed a pawn in order to obtain a big lead in development, but Black has
a solid position in the center and a material advantage, which ensures a
complicated battle with chances for both sides} Nd7 14. Kh1 (14. f5 Be7 15. Qd4
{the threat is Nb1, winning the queen} b5 $1 16. Kh1 Ne5 17. Rf4 {[%cal Yf4h4]}
h4 $1 18. Raf1 Bd7 $17 {[%cal Ga8c8] Black managed to consolidate his position
very well - Popov,I (2594) -Shomoev,A (2559) RUS-chT Dagomys 2008 (10) 0-1})
14... h4 $1 {this advance can help Black's development} 15. h3 (15. Rad1 h3 $1
16. g3 b5 {[%cal Gc8b7] the bishop seems stronger on b7 now that the diagonal
is weakened} 17. Nb1 Qa4 18. Qe3 b4 $5 19. Rd4 a5 20. Nc3 Qc6 21. Nd5 Qb7 $1
22. Bb5 Bg7 {White's position looks very active but two of his pieces are
hanging. Black only needs to neutralize his tactical resources,} 23. Re1 Kf8 {
[%cal Gb7b5]} 24. a4 f5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] ;Gashimov,V (2625)-Palac,M (2561) EU-ch
7th Kusadasi 2006 (7) 0-1 attacking a third piece, Black is winning -}) 15...
Be7 16. Rad1 (16. Nb1 {was played in the most recent game in this line -
