1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 8. Bh4
Qb6 9. Qd2 $5 {The classical main line. If you thought the previous chapters
were long or too theoretical, please take a cup of coffee because now we are
going to see the really long theoretical lines. Still, I think we are not
about to see a monster or something like that. Actually, I should confess that
for a long time I postponed to study a decent line against 6.Bg5, always with
the same excuse "it's too much theory to remember", and It was a pleasant
surprise to realize that it was much fewer lines than I had imagined.} Qxb2
10. Rb1 (10. Nb3 $6 {this is an option against the regular Poisoned Pawn, but
in this case is at least dubious, as with the bishop on h4 Black has the
important idea} Be7 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 11. Bxf6 (11. Bf2 {prevents White's
tactical idea, but Black has no problems now to develop his pieces with a
healthy pawn up} Nc6 12. Be2 d5 $1 13. Rb1 Qxc3 14. Qxc3 Bb4 $17 {Ziska,H 
(2474)-Palliser,R (2453) BCF-chT 1213 (4NCL) 2012 (2.163) 0-1}) (11. e5 $5 {
this looks like a practical decision that one would take at the board, looking
for complications} dxe5 12. a3 $6 {[%cal Ya1a2,Gc3a4]} ({in the notes of the
game, Nielsen says he was expecting} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Na4 Qa3 14. Nb6 O-O $1 {
considering Black's position better. In fact, after} 15. Nxa8 Rd8 16. Qe2 Nc6 {
Black is really much better, for example} 17. Rd1 Qb4+ $1 18. Rd2 exf4 19. Kd1
e5 $17 {[%csl Ra8] even being a full rook down(!), Black has better pieces and
too many pawns, apart from the trapped Na8}) 12... exf4 $1 13. Bf2 $1 (13. Ra2
Ne4 $1 14. Rxb2 Bxh4+ 15. g3 Nxd2 $19) 13... Nd5 14. Bd4 {[%csl Yb2] ;Guseinov,
G (2584) -Nielsen,P (2670) EU-ch 12th Aix les Bains 2011 (3) 1-0} (14. Nxd5
Qe5+ $1 {is a nice intermediate check}) 14... Nc6 $1 {would had solved the
problem of the Black queen} 15. Nxd5 (15. Ra2 Bh4+ $1 16. g3 Nxd4 $19 {[%cal
Gd4f3]}) (15. Bxg7 Bh4+ $1 16. g3 fxg3 17. hxg3 Bxg3+ 18. Kd1 Rg8 19. Nxd5 Qxg7
$19 {[%cal Yg3c7]}) 15... Nxd4 16. Nc7+ Kf8 17. Qxd4 Qxd4 18. Nxd4 Ra7 $19 {
[%csl Gc7] the knight ends up trapped in a funny way on c7. Black regains the
piece and is winning}) (11. a3 {and 11.a4 are similar} Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Bxh4+ 13.
g3 Bf6 $1 14. Nxd6+ Ke7 {[%cal Gf6c3,Yh8d8] and Black is very active} 15. Ne4
Rd8 16. Qb4+ Ke8 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Rb1 Nc6 $17) 11... Bxf6 12. Na4 {[%cal
Ya4b6] the only way to justify White's play} (12. e5 $2 {was played twice. It
looks like a better version for White, but actually, he loses by force now} dxe5
13. Na4 Qa3 14. Nb6 O-O $1 15. Nxa8 Rd8 $1 16. Qa5 Qxa5+ 17. Nxa5 exf4 {
[%csl Ya1][%cal Gf6c3]} 18. Nb3 $8 b5 $1 {[%cal Yc8b7]} 19. Be2 {Weichhold,P 
(2428) -Sadzikowski, D (2548) POL-chT Poland 2017 (6.3) 1-0 Black gave a check
on c3 first, which only helped White. Instead, the direct} Bxa1 {would win} 20.
Nxa1 Bb7 21. Bf3 Bxf3 22. gxf3 Nd7 23. Nc7 Nc5 {[%csl Rc7] and the knight gets
trapped on c7. If} 24. Nb3 Nxb3 25. axb3 Rc8 26. Nxa6 Ra8 $19 {[%cal Ra8a1]})
12... Qa3 13. Nb6 Bxa1 14. Nxa1 $146 (14. Nxa8 $2 Bf6 15. Nb6 O-O $19 {Garcia
Playa, D (1821) -Jimenez Ortiz, G (1883) Cerdanyola del Valles op-A 29th 2011 (5)
0-1}) 14... Qc5 $5 {the most accurate} (14... O-O 15. Nxa8 Qc5 {is a forced
draw after} 16. Nb3 Qa7 17. Nc7 Qb6 18. Na8 Qa7 $11) 15. Nxa8 b6 {[%csl Ya8]
