1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 8. Bh4
Qb6 9. a3 {The modern main line, and probably White's best attempt against the
Modern Poisoned Pawn. In the classical line (without h6), this move is not
that promising for White, as the bishop would be on g5, but in this case, he
can claim that h6 has helped him: The following moves are Bf2, Qf3 and 0-0-0,
with the most aggressive set-up possible. Although many top GM's have played
this line recently, Vachier-Lagrave is for sure the guy to follow on the Black
side, as he has played it many times, contributing a lot to the line's
development.} Be7 {[%cal Gf6e4]} (9... Qxb2 $4 10. Na4 $19 {[%csl Rb2] is the
trap}) 10. Bf2 (10. Qd3 $5 {was played by Caruana as an attempt to catch a
