1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Nb3 $5 {In the last
years, due to the high level of preparation and enormous theoretical wear of
the main lines, White started to look for literally any possible option on his
6th move. This and the last chapter of this database will be dedicated to two
aggressive sidelines. When the search for alternatives began, the knight's
retreat was the first attempt, coming as a bomb after some interesting games
by polish GM Bartel against Najdorf's experts such as Gelfand and Wojtaszek,
and was tried later by many grandmasters. The basic idea is that this
apparently unnecessary move is played in many lines of the Najdorf anyway. By
waiting for Black to choose a set-up, White stays rather flexible in his
development scheme.} e6 {The main move, and also my suggestion. Black has
other options, of course.} (6... Nc6 {also looks playable, but I prefer to
keep the knight flexible on b8}) ({I think} 6... e5 {is a bit pointless: Black
just achieves a position that resembles the 6.Be2 line, however, White has not
developed any of his bishops yet!} 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 9. Qd3 O-O 10.
O-O-O Be7 11. Nd5 Bg5+ 12. Kb1 Be6 13. g3 $1 {White finds a nice task for his
light-squared bishop} Nc6 14. h4 Be7 15. Bh3 $1 Bxd5 16. Qxd5 $14 {[%cal Yh3c8]
with pleasant advantage for White - Grischuk, A (2737)-Amonatov, F (2620) Wch
Rapid Doha rapid 2016 (13) 1-0}) (6... g6 {transposing to Dragon positions can
also be risky, although you can find some strong grandmasters playing this way}
7. Be2 Bg7 8. g4 $5 h6 $2 {Black prevents g5 but will have problems to castle}
(8... Nc6 {is correct}) 9. Be3 Nc6 10. f3 b5 11. Qd2 Be6 12. O-O-O Rc8 13. Kb1
Ne5 14. h4 $36 {Bartel,M (2625)-Artemiev,V (2674) Moscow Aeroflot op-A 15th
2016 (6) 1-0}) (6... b5 $2 {is often premature if Black has not made any
preparatory moves, and this position is no exception:} 7. a4 $1 b4 8. Nd5 e6 9.
Nxf6+ Qxf6 10. g3 $5 {with nice development for White}) 7. g4 $1 {This was
Bartel's idea, White can play some kind of Keres Attack. This also resembles
the 6.h3 lines, that will be analyzed in the next database.} b5 $1 {Black can
also develop in an active way, so I think it is a good option to go for a
double-edged middlegame.} 8. Bg2 (8. a3 {can be played now, and after} Bb7 9.
Bg2 Nfd7 $1 10. g5 {we reach the position from 10.a3 by transposition}) (8. g5
{is too hasty} b4 $1 9. gxf6 (9. Na4 Nxe4 10. Bg2 d5 11. Bxe4 Bd7 $1 {without
this move, Black would have problems with a future Nb6} 12. Nac5 dxe4 $15) 9...
bxc3 10. e5 $2 (10. Qf3 Qxf6 11. Qxf6 gxf6 12. bxc3 Rg8 {is fine for Black})
10... Bb7 11. Rg1 gxf6 12. bxc3 fxe5 13. Qh5 {Black is basically winning, but
somehow he managed to lose the game} Nd7 14. Bg5 Qc7 15. Rg3 {Bellahcene,B 
(2493)-Baert,A (2210) Gibraltar Masters 15th 2017 (8) 1-0} Be4 $19 {[%cal
Ge4g6] seems the easiest way to consolidate the advantage}) 8... Bb7 9. g5 Nfd7
{This is not the only option, but I think it is the most fighting one.} (9...
b4 $5 {lead to some complications after} 10. Nd5 $1 exd5 $1 ({caught by
surprise, Wojtaszek played} 10... Nxd5 11. exd5 e5 {but then} 12. a3 $1 {
gave White a very active position on the queenside, with a clear advantage -
Bartel, M (2625)-Wojtaszek,R (2713) POL-ch Poznan 2016 (5) 1-0}) 11. gxf6 dxe4
{the position arising is very uncommon and also difficult to assess: Black is
a pawn up, but has some weaknesses and is very much behind in development.
White definitely has compensation for the pawn and can develop in many
different ways. I think in practice it is an annoying task for Black as
White's play is much easier and pleasant, while Black needs to defend the
position and find accurate and often only moves}) 10. Be3 {The most played in
an unexplored territory, as this position has occurred in less than 20 games in
tournament practice.} (10. a3 {seems very natural, and is the second most
played} Nc6 {from experience, I realized that Black should develop the
queenside as early as possible in order to get counterplay, so saving the move
Be7, in order to activate the pieces on the other side, is a good idea. Also
Black can later play h6 to weaken White's pawns sometimes.} 11. h4 (11. O-O {
Black had a very clever idea now} g6 $1 12. f4 h6 $1 {a very instructive way
of exploiting White's over-extended kingside} 13. gxh6 Qh4 $132 {Gunnarsson,J 
(2472) -Steingrimsson,H (2583) Icelandic Open 2018 2018 (5.5) 1/2-1/2}) (11. f4
{Bedia,M (2431)-Potrekeev,P (2195) Gelendzhik op 13th 2017 (8) 1-0} h6 $1 {
this was played by Black on the next move, but it is even stronger right now}
12. h4 hxg5 13. hxg5 Rxh1+ 14. Bxh1 Qb6 $36 {[%cal Yb6g1]}) 11... h6 $1 {
this seems a good way to neutralize White's initiative on the kingside} (11...
Be7 12. f4 h6 13. Qg4 b4 $132 {Nepomniachtchi,I (2751)-Oparin,G (2604) Zuerich
Chess Challenge Blitz2 6th blitz 2017 (7) 0-1}) 12. Qg4 {Riff,J (2515)-Caruana,
F (2675) SUI-chT Switzerland 2010 (6.2) 1/2-1/2} (12. gxh6 gxh6 {[%cal Yh8g8]})
(12. g6 $5 fxg6 $13) 12... Nce5 13. Qg3 Rc8 14. f4 {Black has an interesting
sacrifice now} hxg5 $1 15. fxe5 (15. hxg5 Rxh1+ 16. Bxh1 Nc4 {[%csl Yb2] is
fine for Black, as the Bc1 can't be developed}) 15... gxh4 16. Qe3 Nxe5 $13 {
[%cal Yf8e7,Yg7g5,Yg5g4,Ge5c4] the position is very balanced, but Black's
compensation for the piece seems at least sufficient}) (10. f4 {allows the
same idea} h6 $1 11. h4 (11. gxh6 Rxh6 $15) (11. g6 $5 Qh4+ $1 12. Kf1 Nc6 $1 {
Black should take care with Na5} 13. gxf7+ Kxf7 $13 {and both sides should
take care of their kings}) 11... hxg5 12. hxg5 Rxh1+ 13. Bxh1 b4 14. Ne2 a5 $36
{Smirin,I (2670)-Jumabayev,R (2611) Moscow Aeroflot op-A 16th 2017 (8) 1/2-1/2}
) (10. O-O Be7 11. f4 O-O 12. Qg4 (12. a3 Nc6 13. Rf3 Re8 14. Rg3 Rc8 15. h4 {
Kravtsiv,M (2685)-Vykouk,J (2445) 19th ch-EUR Indiv 2018 2018 (1.14) 1/2-1/2}
Bf8 16. h5 Ne7 $5 $132 {[%cal Yd6d5] An interesting regroupment for Black,
after which he is ready to play d5, with counter-chances}) 12... Re8 13. Be3
Nc6 14. Rad1 {Demchenko,A (2645)-Areshchenko,A (2652) FIDE World Cup 2017 (1.2)
1-0} b4 15. Ne2 (15. Na4 Na5) 15... Rc8 16. Ng3 Bf8 17. h4 Na5 $132) (10. h4
Nc6 11. f4 b4 12. Ne2 {Bartel,M (2653)-Zubov,A (2612) EU-ch 17th Gjakova 2016 
(5) 1/2-1/2} h6 $5 {this thematic idea seems a nice solution for Black
whenever it is possible} 13. f5 $5 (13. g6 $5 fxg6 14. Nbd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Qe7
16. Qg4 Nf6 $1 17. Qxg6+ Qf7 {and Black is fine}) 13... e5 $1 14. g6 fxg6 15.
fxg6 Be7 {with chances for both sides, but Black shouldn't be worse, for
example} 16. O-O $1 (16. Qd5 $2 Bxh4+ 17. Kd1 Rf8 $17) 16... Bxh4 17. Qxd6 (17.
Qd5 Qb6+ 18. Kh1 O-O-O $1) 17... Qb6+ 18. Kh1 Ne7 $1 $11) (10. Bf4 $6 {seems a
bit strange - Valuet, B (2284)-Dubessay,B (2348) Juvisy sur Orge 2013 (4) 0-1}
Ne5 $1 {and Black is fine, for example} 11. a3 (11. Bxe5 dxe5 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8
13. O-O-O+ Kc7 $15 {is a better endgame for Black}) 11... Nbd7 12. Qe2 Rc8 $15
{[%cal Yh7h6] I think Black already has an easier game, as it is not clear
what White's plan is, and the idea h7-h6 is still on the table.}) 10... Ne5 {
The knight heads to c4. It is curious that Black is making so many moves with
the knight, but since his position is solid and flexible, he will be able to
finish his development.} (10... b4 {taking advantage of the fact that White
didn't play a3 is also possible} 11. Ne2 Ne5 12. Ned4 Nc4 13. Qe2 Nxe3 14. Qxe3
Nd7 15. f4 {Miroshnichenko,E (2616)-Idani,P (2560) Guilan Stars Cup 1st 2016 
(8.6) 1-0} a5 {[%cal Ya5a4,Gd8b6,Ye6e5] and Black is active}) 11. Qe2 Nc4 12.
O-O-O {White has developed almost all of his pieces while Black embarked on
the task of eliminating the Be3. However, there are no easy ways to open the
position or create serious threats, so White is not able to use his lead in
development to get an advantage.} Nd7 13. f4 Be7 14. h4 {Now, after} ({if
White tries to save the bishop} 14. Bd4 e5 $5 15. Bf2 (15. fxe5 Bxg5+ {wins a
pawn}) 15... exf4 16. h4 O-O {[%cal Yd7e5,Yd8c7] is ok for Black}) 14... Nxe3
15. Qxe3 b4 $1 16. Ne2 a5 $1 {Black is even taking the initiative first in
queenside.} 17. Nbd4 {[%cal Yd4b5]} Qb6 18. Rh3 g6 $1 {A good move, avoiding
any tension on the kingside.} 19. h5 O-O-O $5 {And Black is fine. The bishop
pair and White's over-extended pawns on the kingside are good reasons to play
for a win - Salinas Herrera, P (2438)-Debarshi, M (2301) Barcelona Sant Marti
op-A 19th 2017 (3) 0-1} *

