1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Rg1 {[%cal Gg2g4] Like
in the previous chapter, White wants to advance his g-pawn, although this time
he is very clear about his intentions. These two last chapters provide a nice
introduction to 6.h3, which will be seen in the third database.} e5 {This move
makes more sense here than in the 6.Nb3 line, and seems the most practical
solution against White's aggressive intentions.} 7. Nb3 Be6 {[%cal Yd6d5] d5
can't be prevented, and the ensuing simplifications lead to an endgame that
should be balanced.} 8. g4 (8. Bg5 Nbd7 {[%cal Yh7h6] It wouldn't make sense
for White to have the rook on g1 in this position}) 8... d5 $1 9. exd5 (9. g5 {
is another way to reach the endgame, depriving Black of his castling right.}
Nxe4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Bg2 (12. Be3 {is a different move order,
but inferior for White} Kc7 13. Bg2 {I found this example by Sasikiran very
instructive} h6 $1 14. gxh6 g6 $1 {a typical transformation on the kingside,
which gives Black the easier game} 15. Bxe4 Nd7 16. O-O-O Bxh6 17. Rg3 {
Prasad, D (2465)-Sasikiran,K (2569) IND-ch 39th Nagpur 2002 (4) 0-1} Bxe3+ 18.
Rxe3 Rac8 $15 {Black's better structure gives him nice winning chances}) 12...
Kc7 13. Bxe4 Nc6 {this is a similar way of development as if Black had played
0-0-0. It takes more time but is still fine.} 14. Be3 (14. f4 {Morais,G (2336)
-Debevec,B (2310) W-ch32 prel06 email 2008 1/2-1/2} g6 {seems solid enough for
Black} 15. fxe5 h6 $1 16. h4 Nxe5 17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Nc5 Bf5 $1 19. O-O-O Bxe4 20.
Nxe4 Nd3+ $1 21. Rxd3 Bxf4+ 22. Kb1 hxg5 23. hxg5 Rad8 $11) 14... Rd8 {[%cal
Yd8d1] In the end, it is Black who prevents his opponent from castling} 15. Nc5
(15. c3 {Didenot Chirinos,C (2069)-Velasquez Guerra,E (1953) Cumana Vergara
Sequera Memorial 2014 (2.1) 0-1} g6 $5 {[%cal Yh7h6]} 16. h4 h6 17. Nd2 hxg5
18. hxg5 Ne7 $15 {[%cal Ge7d5,Ge7f5]}) (15. Rd1 Rxd1+ 16. Kxd1 h6 $1 17. gxh6
g6 {[%cal Yf8h6] was fine for Black, as usual - Gueting,J-Juhnke,K (2305)
Oberliga Nord W 9495 1994 (3.4) 1/2-1/2}) 15... Bxc5 16. Bxc5 {Landa,K (2542)
-Nevostrujev, V (2466) RUS-chT St Petersburg 1999 (2) 1/2-1/2} Bd5 $5 17. Bxd5
(17. Bd3 b6 18. Be3 Nb4 {is fine for Black}) 17... Rxd5 18. Be3 Rhd8 $11 {
[%cal Yc6e7,Ye7f5,Yc6d4,Gf7f5] Black has some ideas like Nd4-f5 or Ne7-f5,
advancing the kingside majority... but objectively speaking, the most likely
result is a draw of course}) 9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Be3 (11. Qxd5 Bxd5 12.
Be3 Nc6 13. O-O-O O-O-O {is just another move order}) 11... Nc6 12. Qxd5 Bxd5
13. O-O-O O-O-O {The endgame was reached more or less by force and with
natural moves. Such Sicilian endgames tend to be pleasant for Black, although
with correct play by both sides the natural result should be a draw.} 14. Bb6 (
14. Be2 {is also natural, but here Black controls the b6-square} Kc7 15. c4 {
Petrosian, T (2539) -Karjakin, S (2580) ACP Blitz Octofinal-C 3rd blitz 2004 (1)
1/2-1/2} (15. c3 Be7 16. g5 {Radovanovic,D (2337)-Uzumcu,A (2143) Veliko
Gradiste Silver Lake op-A 2017 (7) 1-0 it is important to understand that the
way of losing such equal endgames is making small concessions to the opponent until the position becomes unpleasant enough to make mistakes. This game is a
good example because Black played g6? and ended up with a useless majority on
the kingside - while} h6 $1 17. gxh6 g6 $1 {[%cal Ge7f8] was a much better way
to play, keeping the kingside structure healthy}) 15... Be4 16. Rxd8 Nxd8 17.
f4 (17. f3 Bg6 $11) 17... exf4 18. Bxf4+ Bd6 19. Bxd6+ Kxd6 $11) ({another
instructive game went} 14. g5 Kc7 15. Bh3 $2 {a poor place for the bishop.
Black's play was very smart now} g6 $1 ({the direct} 15... h6 {would not be so
good due} 16. g6 $1) 16. f4 h6 $1 {Black will end up in a better endgame now}
17. fxe5 hxg5 18. Bxg5 Bh6 $1 19. Bxh6 Rxh6 20. Bg2 Bxg2 21. Rxd8 Kxd8 22. Rxg2
Nxe5 $17 {[%csl Gf7] With a passed pawn and the h2-pawn being weak, Black has
a clear advantage - Belousov, D (2340)-Antipov,M (2457) Chigorin Memorial 20th
2012 (9) 0-1}) 14... Rd6 {This endgame has been played in a few correspondence
games too.} 15. a3 (15. Bc5 Rd8 16. Bb6 $11) (15. c4 {my advise for such
positions is to avoid pawn moves unless they are necessary} Be4 16. Rxd6 Bxd6
17. Nd2 Bg6 {[%cal Yg6b1] thanks to c4 the bishop has a great diagonal now} 18.
a3 Bc7 19. Bxc7 Kxc7 20. Rg3 {Bizopoulos,A (2150)-Klimov,A (2451) Wch U18 Vung
Tau 2008 (10) 0-1} f6 $15 {[%cal Gg6f7,Gc6d4] the other drawback of c4 is the
d4-square, which is already a strategic achievement for Black}) (15. c3 Be7 16.
g5 Be6 $1 {after g5, Black has some lines and ideas on the kingside} 17. Rxd6
Bxd6 18. h4 h6 $1 19. g6 (19. gxh6 Rxh6 20. Rxg7 Rxh4 {seems easier for Black
in practice}) 19... f6 20. Bg2 h5 21. Nc5 Bxc5 22. Bxc5 Kc7 23. Rd1 Re8 $11 {
Kokorin,V (2358)-Yurov,A (2330) RUS WS MN05 email 2010 1/2-1/2} 24. Bf3 Bf5 $1)
(15. g5 Be6 16. Bg2 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Be7 18. h4 h6 $1 {this forces White to take
active measures} 19. Nc5 hxg5 20. Nxe6 fxe6 21. hxg5 Bxg5+ 22. Kb1 Rh2 {
and Black is fine - Simmelink,J (2297)-Bernal Varela,N (2172) CFriend
RH-2005-0-00029 email 2005 (1) 1/2-1/2}) 15... Bxb3 $5 {Very concrete decision
by Black, damaging the queenside pawns in order to ruin White's majority.} (
15... Be7 {is interesting, as Black wants to provoke g5 to get some squares
and h6-ideas on the kingside} 16. g5 Be6 17. Rxd6 Bxd6 {Rosso,P (2211)
-Myakonikikh,D (2338) W-ch33 prel03 email 2009 1/2-1/2}) 16. Rxd6 (16. cxb3 Nd4
17. Bxd4 exd4 $11 {[%cal Yf8e7,Ye7f6]}) 16... Bxd6 17. cxb3 Bc7 18. Be3 Nd4 19.
Bxd4 exd4 $11 {Van Foreest,J (2605) -Sasikiran,K (2661) Sitges Sunway op 2016 
(4) 1/2-1/2} *

